snippet.textDisplay:
[[NOTE: I am in no way criticizing you for any mistakes. This is constructive criticism. If anything, this far exceeds my artistic ability]]

I wanted to point out that the reason your nose may appear bigger in your drawing is because the farthest edge of the paint dripping down the right nostril (if you’re mirroring) intersects vertically with the right eye’s eastern edge of the iris.

Edit: in the photo, the paint covers part of your nostril, but in the drawing, the paint looks as if it was like “Pin the tail on the Donkey,” but the paint was placed slightly left of where it should be.

2nd Edit: Mouth extends slightly more horizontal than it should, while the distance between the bottom edge of the lower lip and the chin/jawline is decreased.

Nevertheless, love your content. It’s good stuff. Thanks for doing what you do, my dude.

snippet.textDisplay: Please help me understand how this mind-blowing thing is a thing!  I'm not surprised Jazza Thought this technique had to be faked and there are some things I'd love to understand better here.  The first thing you learn when learning drawing is to start by roughing things in throughout the space you have and then flesh out details and most of art education follows that pattern.  This "printer method" seems like an utterly counterintuitive and unhelpful way to draw, and yet people can apparently do it to a ridiculously high standard.  Are they just so well trained that they decided to perfect this stunt for the heck of it, or is there some way that this opposite to most people approach can have advantages for some people?  How skilled does one have to be for doing a sketch of any complication at al in this method to be at all a useful exercise?  What mental processes and skills are necessary to do it well and with any degree of efficiency?  This is just so far out of what I can imagine being real.   Kudos to you for even trying, Jazza, and I too am amazed by how well you managed.

snippet.textDisplay: Drawing "like a printer" is not impressive. Take a white piece of paper, then draw a few random dots on it. Some people will be able to reproduce the dots very close in another piece of paper, some won't. Those who can get the dots almost exact will be able to draw "like a printer" reproducing a photo row by row. I see no value in a human spending hours creating an exact copy of what's already there. That's not art and it's pointless, it's just like people who can fold their tongue backwards or move their ears.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is a lot back lash towards artist that use projection methods and the such; however, many of the old masters used camera lucida, camera obscura, and other projection methods for their drawings/sketches before painting! I feel like as long as the image projected is copyright free/ your own image then it generally okay to me. A few of my college art professors even encouraged it for pre-sketches for large paintings.

My only qualm with the examples shown in jazz’s videos is that fact that they’re NOT using copyright free images but instead taking from photographers. Just because there’s a celebrity in a photo doesn’t mean the photo belongs to no one. But that’s neither here nor there and a whole other conversation 🤣

snippet.textDisplay: i don't know why your so surprised? Because i'm sure their is people who cheat. but i'm also sure its pretty easy to study how a printer works and study its movements and all that and then practice those exact same skills and over time you most certainly would be able to do it easily. I've seen people who are non drawers use the way printers work, in order to create other things even to get accuracy down to a almost impossible method. Even free ranging of course they used a series of methods that largely used some mechanics but its not surprising me that someone could sit for hundreds of thousands of hours practicing until they could do it on their own. But i would be more surprised if they would be able to go back to regular drawing after that as it seems likely that they would be stuck drawing only in that method or some variation of it.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is another way to draw like a printer, make drawing quite easy, proove it with cameras and still cheat.

Setup of this cheat would be on the other hand quite scientific and challenging.

It all comes down to physics and carefull setup of flickering.
If your camera records at a fixed fps rate X and you are able to project an image from a projector straight on to the paper with another fixed refresh rate Y, syncing both devices (adjusting Y and X) can give an effect that a human eye would see an image on the paper, but cameras would only capture the 'bits of time' when the projector/screen is dark.

That way you could draw line by line seeing the picture overlay straight on the paper, but on the camera it would look like you had no help at all.

Come to think of it, this would make a very interesting video to shoot :)

EDIT: another method, easier to do and explain would be to use polarized light. It would be possible to emit polarized light onto the paper, block it from the camera (or cameras) but allow the human eye to see it. :3

It all comes down to physics and carefull setup of flickering.
If your camera records at a fixed fps rate X and you are able to project an image from a projector straight on to the paper with another fixed refresh rate Y, syncing both devices (adjusting Y  and X) can give an effect that a human eye would see an image on the paper, but cameras would only capture the 'bits of time' when the projector/screen is dark.

That way you could draw line by line seeing the picture overlay straight on the paper, but on the camera it would look like you had no help at all. 

Come to think of it, this would make a very interesting video to shoot :)

EDIT: another method, easier to do and explain would be to use polarized light. It would be possible to emit polarized light onto the paper, block it from the camera (or cameras) but allow the human eye to see it. :3
